      <div xml:id="NA162-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu “uṭaṉpōtuval” (EV: uṭaṉvaruvēṉ) eṉṟa talaivikkut (ET: talaimakaṭkut; ETv: eṉṟāṭkut) talaivaṉ coṟṟatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE said to HER who said “I will elope”.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA162">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            maṉaiyuṟai puṟaviṉ ceṅkāṟ pēṭaik</l>
<l>            kāmar tuṇaiyoṭu cēval cērap</l>
<l>            pulampiṉ ṟeḻutarum puṉkaṇ mālait</l>
<l>            taṉiyē yirutta lāṟṟē ṉeṉṟuniṉ</l>
<l>            paṉivā ruṇkaṇ paitala kaluḻa </l>
<l>            nummoṭu varuva leṉṟi yemmoṭu</l>
<l>            perumpeyart tantai nīṭupukaḻ neṭunakar</l>
<l>            yāyoṭu naṉimika maṭavai muṉātu</l>
<l>            vēli ṉiṟṟit tōyā neṭuvīḻ</l>
<l>            vaḻinā ḷūcaliṟ kōṭai tūkkutoṟun </l>
<l>            tuñcupiṭi varuṭu mattam</l>
<l>            vallai yākuta lollumō niṉakkē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent3">“Solitude on sorrowful evening, rising irresistably<note place="foot">Thus a quite strong rendering of <term xml:lang="ta">eḻu-tarum</term>, an auxiliary construction that might have a very emotive value here.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">endowed with loneliness<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">pulampiṉṟu</term> can be analysed in two ways, either as a n.sg. of the p.a. or as n.sg. of the appellative noun. I prefer the latter possibility, because the aspect would be a problem here. T.V.G. nevertheless explains it as a finite verb in <term xml:lang="ta">muṟṟeccam</term> function, for the sake of the metrical foot.</note>, when the cock joins with [its] desired mate,</l>
<l rend="indent">the red-legged female of the dove staying in the house.</l>
<l rend="indent">I cannot bear [it]”,<note place="foot">The syntactical structure of line 3 + 4 can be interpreted in three ways. The first version pays heed to the particle mark of <term xml:lang="ta">taṉiyē</term>, while version b is the one chosen by T.V.G.</note> saying so while your</l>
<l rend="indent2">kajal eyes, overflowing with dew, dimned from sufferings,</l>
<l>you said 'I will come with you.'</l>
<l>With us<note place="foot">The position of the <term xml:lang="ta">emmoṭu</term> is slightly awkward; it might have to be connected with the poem end.</note>, will it be possible for you to be strong [enough] for the road</l>
<l rend="indent">where the fig tree’s long aerial roots, that don't touch [the ground],</l>
<l rend="indent">spear-like, rub the sleeping elephant cow</l>
<l rend="indent2">whenever the west wind lifts [them], like a swing on sucessive days,</l>
<l rend="indent">− for you who previously(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">muṉātu</term> seems best taken here as an adverb of time, though then we would prefer it to precede <term xml:lang="ta">maṭavai</term>. (T.V.G. gives two conflicting explanations, both relating to time: either in the early morning or before marriage.)</note> had no experience at all, with [your] mother</l>
<l rend="indent">in the long-praised large mansion of [your] father with great name?</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="3+4b">
<l>    “I cannot bear to be alone</l>
<l> 	on sorrowful evening that rises irresistably, endowed with loneliness...”</l>
</lg>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="3+4c">
<l>    “Sorrowful evening, rising irresistably, is full of loneliness.</l>
<l> 	I cannot bear to be alone.”</l>
</lg>
        </lg>
